unwiredbrain:
I'm not sure whether this is strictly Crossfilter-related, but you can get away with it with a couple of higher-order functions:

``` js
var data = [
  ['ABC', 'ABCD', 'ABCDEF', 'abcd', 'a', 'Abcdef', 'Abcderfg', 'A', 'ABC'],
  ['ABCD', 'ABC', 'ABCDEF', 'abc', 'AB', 'Abcdef', 'abcd', 'ABC', 'ABC'],
  ['Abcderfg', 'ABC', 'ABCDEFGH', 'abc', 'A', 'ABCDEF', 'abcd', 'AB', 'ABC'],
  [],
  [''],
  ['', 'A'],
  ['AA', ''],
  ['ABC', 'AB'],
  ['ABCDE', '', 'ABCD']
];

var max = data.map(function (record) {
  return record.reduce(function (previous, current) {
    return Math.max(previous, current.length);
  }, 0);
});

console.log(max); // Outputs [8, 6, 8, 0, 0, 1, 2, 3, 5]
```

Beware that this approach is not 100% foolproof as by "just" looking at the `length` property you may get [unexpected results](https://mathiasbynens.be/notes/javascript-unicode).
. Oh, okay, I think I see what you mean: you're scanning "vertically" rather than "horizontally," right?
And you're assuming that all the rows in such a rectangular matrix have the exact same number of columns, correct?

Gotta say that I'm not fluent with Crossfilter so I'm not sure if I can be of any help.

I would call `.dimension()` on each column you want to inspect

``` js
var column0 = data.dimension(function (d) {
  return d[0];
});

var column1 = data.dimension(function (d) {
  return d[1];
});
```

then apply some reduce function on each of them.
